    {
      "content": "Upgrade from Mobile Services to Azure App Service",
      "pos": [
        28,
        77
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Learn how to easily upgrade your Mobile Services application to an App Service Mobile App",
      "pos": [
        97,
        186
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Upgrade your existing .NET Azure Mobile Service to App Service",
      "pos": [
        524,
        586
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "App Service Mobile is a new way to build mobile applications using Microsoft Azure.",
      "pos": [
        588,
        671
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To learn more, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">What are Mobile Apps?]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        672,
        715
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This topic describes how to upgrade an existing .NET backend application from Azure Mobile Services to a new App Service Mobile Apps.",
      "pos": [
        717,
        850
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "While you perform this upgrade, your existing Mobile Services application can continue to operate.",
      "pos": [
        851,
        949
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        952,
        1129
      ],
      "content": "When a mobile backend is upgraded to Azure App Service, it has access to all App Service features and are billed according to <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">App Service pricing]</ept>, not Mobile Services pricing."
    },
    {
      "content": "Migrate vs. upgrade",
      "pos": [
        1133,
        1152
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.TIP]</ph> It is recommended that you <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>perform a migration<ept id=\"p1\">](app-service-mobile-migrating-from-mobile-services.md)</ept> before going through an upgrade.",
      "pos": [
        1269,
        1416
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This way, you can put both versions of your application on the same App Service Plan and incur no additional cost.",
      "pos": [
        1417,
        1531
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Improvements in Mobile Apps .NET server SDK",
      "pos": [
        1536,
        1579
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        1581,
        1715
      ],
      "content": "Upgrading to the new <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Mobile Apps SDK<ept id=\"p1\">](https://www.nuget.org/packages/Microsoft.Azure.Mobile.Server/)</ept> provides the following benefits:"
    },
    {
      "content": "More flexibility on NuGet dependencies.",
      "pos": [
        1719,
        1758
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The hosting environment no longer provides its own versions of NuGet packages, so you can use alternative compatible versions.",
      "pos": [
        1759,
        1885
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, if there are new critical bugfixes or security updates to the Mobile Server SDK or dependencies, you must update your service manually.",
      "pos": [
        1886,
        2030
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "More flexibility in the mobile SDK.",
      "pos": [
        2034,
        2069
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can explicitly control which features and routes are set up, such as authentication, table APIs, and the push registration endpoint.",
      "pos": [
        2070,
        2206
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To learn more, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>How to use the .NET server SDK for Azure Mobile Apps<ept id=\"p1\">](app-service-mobile-net-upgrading-from-mobile-services.md#server-project-setup)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        2207,
        2360
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Support for other ASP.NET project types and routes.",
      "pos": [
        2364,
        2415
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can now host MVC and Web API controllers in the same project as your mobile backend project.",
      "pos": [
        2416,
        2512
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Support for new App Service authentication features, which allow you to use a common authentication configuration across your web and mobile apps.",
      "pos": [
        2516,
        2662
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        2666,
        2711
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"overview\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Basic upgrade overview"
    },
    {
      "content": "In many cases, upgrading will be as simple as switching to the new Mobile Apps server SDK and republishing your code onto a new Mobile App instance.",
      "pos": [
        2713,
        2861
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There are, however some scenarios which will require some additional configuration, such as advanced authentication scenarios and working with scheduled jobs.",
      "pos": [
        2862,
        3020
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Each of these is covered in the later sections.",
      "pos": [
        3021,
        3068
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.TIP]</ph> It is advised that you read and understand the rest of this topic completely before starting an upgrade.",
      "pos": [
        3071,
        3187
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Make note of any features you use which are called out below.",
      "pos": [
        3188,
        3249
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Mobile Services client SDKs are <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>not<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> compatible with the new Mobile Apps server SDK.",
      "pos": [
        3251,
        3342
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In order to provide continuity of service for your app, you should not publish changes to a site currently serving published clients.",
      "pos": [
        3343,
        3476
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Instead, you should create a new mobile app that serves as a duplicate.",
      "pos": [
        3477,
        3548
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can put this application on the same App Service plan to avoid incurring additional financial cost.",
      "pos": [
        3549,
        3652
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You will then have two versions of the application: one which stays the same and serves published apps in the wild, and the other which you can then upgrade and target with a new client release.",
      "pos": [
        3654,
        3848
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can move and test your code at your pace, but you should make sure that any bug fixes you make get applied to both.",
      "pos": [
        3849,
        3968
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Once you feel that a desired number of client apps in the wild have updated to the latest version, you can delete the original migrated app if you desire.",
      "pos": [
        3969,
        4123
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The full outline for the upgrade process is as follows:",
      "pos": [
        4125,
        4180
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Create a new Mobile App",
      "pos": [
        4185,
        4208
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Update the project to use the new Server SDKs",
      "pos": [
        4212,
        4257
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Release a new version of your client application",
      "pos": [
        4261,
        4309
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "(Optional) Delete your original migrated instance",
      "pos": [
        4313,
        4362
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"mobile-app-version\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Creating a second application instance",
      "pos": [
        4366,
        4437
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The first step in upgrading is to create the Mobile App resource which will host the new version of your application.",
      "pos": [
        4438,
        4555
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you have already migrated an existing mobile service, you will want to create this version on the same hosting plan.",
      "pos": [
        4556,
        4675
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Open the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Azure portal]</ept> and navigate to your migrated application.",
      "pos": [
        4676,
        4742
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Make note of the App Service Plan it is running on.",
      "pos": [
        4743,
        4794
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Next, create the second application instance by following the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>.NET backend creation instructions<ept id=\"p1\">](app-service-mobile-dotnet-backend-how-to-use-server-sdk.md#create-app)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        4796,
        4966
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When prompted to select you App Service Plan or \"hosting plan\" choose the plan of your migrated application.",
      "pos": [
        4967,
        5075
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You will likely want to use the same database and Notification Hub as you did in Mobile Services.",
      "pos": [
        5077,
        5174
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can copy these values by opening <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Azure portal]</ept> and navigating to the original application, then click <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Settings<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> &gt; <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Application settings<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        5175,
        5322
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Under <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Connection Strings<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, copy <ph id=\"ph1\">`MS_NotificationHubConnectionString`</ph> and <ph id=\"ph2\">`MS_TableConnectionString`</ph>.",
      "pos": [
        5323,
        5426
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Navigate to your new upgrade site and paste them in, overwriting any existing values.",
      "pos": [
        5427,
        5512
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Repeat this process for any other application settings your app needs.",
      "pos": [
        5513,
        5583
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If not using a migrated service, you can read connection strings and app settings from the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Configure<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> tab of the Mobile Services section of the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p2\">Azure classic portal]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        5584,
        5754
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Make a copy of the ASP.NET project for your application and publish it to your new site.",
      "pos": [
        5756,
        5844
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Using a copy of your client application updated with the new URL, validate that everything works as expected.",
      "pos": [
        5845,
        5954
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Updating the server project",
      "pos": [
        5959,
        5986
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Mobile Apps provides a new <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Mobile App Server SDK]</ept> which provides much of the same functionality as the Mobile Services runtime.",
      "pos": [
        5988,
        6116
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "First, you should remove all references to the Mobile Services packages.",
      "pos": [
        6117,
        6189
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In the NuGet package manager, search for <ph id=\"ph1\">`WindowsAzure.MobileServices.Backend`</ph>.",
      "pos": [
        6190,
        6269
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Most apps will see several packages here, including <ph id=\"ph1\">`WindowsAzure.MobileServices.Backend.Tables`</ph> and <ph id=\"ph2\">`WindowsAzure.MobileServices.Backend.Entity`</ph>.",
      "pos": [
        6270,
        6416
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In such a case, start with the lowest package in the dependency tree, such as <ph id=\"ph1\">`Entity`</ph>, and remove it.",
      "pos": [
        6417,
        6519
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When prompted, do not remove all dependant packages.",
      "pos": [
        6520,
        6572
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Repeat this process until you have removed <ph id=\"ph1\">`WindowsAzure.MobileServices.Backend`</ph> itself.",
      "pos": [
        6573,
        6661
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "At this point you will have a project that no longer references Mobile Services SDKs.",
      "pos": [
        6663,
        6748
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Next you will add references the Mobile Apps SDK.",
      "pos": [
        6750,
        6799
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For this upgrade, most developers will want to download and install the <ph id=\"ph1\">`Micrsoft.Azure.Mobile.Server.Quickstart`</ph> package, as this will pull in the entire required set.",
      "pos": [
        6800,
        6968
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There will be quite a few compiler errors resulting from differences between the SDKs, but these are easy to address and are covered in the rest of this section.",
      "pos": [
        6970,
        7131
      ]
    },
    {
