    {
      "content": "Querying system properties",
      "pos": [
        11357,
        11383
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In Azure Mobile Services, system properties are not sent by default, but only when they are requested using the query string <ph id=\"ph1\">`__systemProperties`</ph>.",
      "pos": [
        11385,
        11531
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In contrast, in Azure Mobile Apps system properties are <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>always selected<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> since they are part of the server SDK object model.",
      "pos": [
        11532,
        11659
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This change mainly impacts custom implementations of domain managers, such as extensions of <ph id=\"ph1\">`MappedEntityDomainManager`</ph>.",
      "pos": [
        11662,
        11782
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In Mobile Services, if a client never requests any system properties, it is possible to use a <ph id=\"ph1\">`MappedEntityDomainManager`</ph> that does not actually map all properties.",
      "pos": [
        11783,
        11947
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, in Azure Mobile Apps, these unmapped properties will cause an error in GET queries.",
      "pos": [
        11948,
        12040
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The easiest way to resolve the issue is to modify your DTOs so that they inherit from <ph id=\"ph1\">`ITableData`</ph> instead of <ph id=\"ph2\">`EntityData`</ph>.",
      "pos": [
        12043,
        12166
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Then, add the <ph id=\"ph1\">`[NotMapped]`</ph> attribute to the fields that should be omitted.",
